  "prompt": "If light does not have mass, then how can it bend due to gravity? How can light have momentum if mass is 0?",
  "response": "These are great questions that touch on some profound and fascinating principles of physics. Let's approach them one by one.\n\n### How can light bend due to gravity?\n\nAccording to Einstein's general theory of relativity, gravity is not a force in the traditional sense but rather a curvature of spacetime. Massive objects, like stars and planets, warp the spacetime around them. When light passes through this curved spacetime, its path appears to bend. \n\nTo visualize this, consider a stretched rubber sheet. If you place a heavy ball in the center, the sheet will curve around the ball. If you then roll a marble across the sheet, its path will bend as it moves through the curved region. Similarly, light follows the curvature of spacetime created by massive objects. This phenomenon is well documented; for example, it has been observed during solar eclipses when the light from stars is bent as it passes near the Sun.\n\n### How can light have momentum if its mass is zero?\n\nMomentum in classical mechanics is usually considered as the product of mass and velocity. However, for light (and other massless particles), we need to rely on the principles of quantum mechanics and relativity.\n\nIn quantum mechanics and special relativity, momentum can exist independently of mass. For photons (the particles of light), their momentum \\( p \\) is given by the equation:\n\\[ p = \\frac{E}{c} \\]\nwhere \\( E \\) is the energy of the photon and \\( c \\) is the speed of light. Since photons possess energy \\( E = h \\nu \\) (where \\( h \\) is Planck\u2019s constant and \\( \\nu \\) is the frequency of the light), they naturally have momentum even though their rest mass is zero.\n\nThus, the momentum of light is derived from its energy and the relationship defined by relativity, not from the classical mass-velocity product. This allows light to exert pressure (known as radiation pressure) and interact dynamically with matter and fields.\n\nThese concepts represent a beautiful union of quantum mechanics and relativity, demonstrating how even particles without mass can exhibit properties normally associated with mass-bearing objects.",
